Bilocal Approximation to Hadronic Structure and Inclusion of Color 

The supergroup  acts on a                        
quark and antidiquark situated at the same point .  At the                       
point  we can consider                        
the action of this supergroup with the same parameters, or one with                       
different parameters.  In the first case we have a global symmetry.  In the                        
second case, if we only deal with bilocal fields the symmetry will be                        
represented by , doubling the supergroup.                        
On the other hand, if any number of points are considered, with                       
different parameters                        
attached to each point, we are led to introduce a local supersymmetry                       
 to which we should add the local color group .                        
Since it is not a                        
fundamental symmetry, we shall not deal with the local  group here.                         
However, the doubling the supergroup is useful for bilocal fields since the                        
decomposition of the adjoint representation of the 728-dimensional                         
group with respect to  gives                       

                        
                       
A further decomposition of the double supergroup into its field with                        
respect to its center of mass coordinates, as will be seen below                       
leads to the decomposition of the 126-dimensional cosets  and                       
 into   of the diagonal . We would have a much tighter and more elegant scheme if we could perform such a decomposition from the start and be able to identify                        
part of the fundametal representation of  with the -dimensional                       
representation of the  subgroup, which means going beyond the                       
 supersymmetry to a smaller supergroup having  as a subgroup. Full description of a bilocal treatment and a minimal scheme where the bilocal treatment gets carried over unchanged into it will be a subject of another publication.                        
                      
Setting up of an effective relativistic theory based on the Dirac equation for the quark and the Klein-Gordon equation for the antiquark, exhibiting invariance under relativistic supersymmetry is needed. This can be achieved by means of an effective Wess-Zumino type Lagrangian constructed out of a gluon field interacting with a vector superfield formed by a quark and an antidiquark. In what follows we will present some preliminary work in this direction.                     

Low-lying baryons occur in the symmetric  representation                       
of , whereas the Pauli principle would have led to the antisymmetrical                         
representation.  This was a crucial fact for the introduction of color degree                        
of freedom based on . Since the quark field                       
transforms like a color triplet and the diquark like a color                       
antitriplet under , the color                        
degrees of freedom of the constituents must be included correctly in order                        
to obtain a correct representation of the q-D system.  Hadronic states must                        
be color singlets.  These are represented by bilocal operators                       
