 meson states.                      
                       
   Switching to the baryon states, the requirement of antisymmetry in color                       
and symmetry in spin-flavor indices gives the                        
representation for . The  multiplets have negative                       
parity and have mixed spin-flavor symmetry.                       
They belong to the representation  of  and                       
are represented by the states  which are  in                       
number.  On the whole, these  states                       
account for all the observed low-lying baryon states obtained from                        
.  A similar analysis can be carried out for the                       
exotic meson states , where the diquark and the                       
antidiquark can be bound in an  or  state with                       
opposite parities.                       


Color Algebra and Octonions 

The exact, unbroken color group
 is the
backbone of the strong interaction. It is worthwhile to understand its role in the
diquark picture more clearly.

Two of the colored quarks in the baryon combine into an anti-triplet 
, . The  partner of the diquark and the  partner 
of the nucleon do not
exist. In hadron dynamics the only color combinations to consider
are  and . These relations imply 
the existence of split octonion units through
a representation of the Grassmann algebra , . What is a bit strange is that 
operators , unlike ordinary fermionic operators, are not associative. We also have 
