Possible Strategy for an Improved Skyrmion Model for Hadrons 

We have seen that the two-body potential models for the  and  bound state systems give a good description of hadrons when the potentials are extracted from QCD. In this case gluons are integrated out but the quark degrees of freedom remain. The model reflects the basic symmetries of QCD: its flavor independence, its approximate spin independence of the confining forces, the vector nature of gluons (Coulomb force at short distances) and its chiral invariance broken by  condensates. In addition we have  structure for mesons and  or  structure for baryons giving the corresponding representations of  for low lying hadrons and its supersymmetric extension .

The skyrmion model, to be successful must reflect these symmetries. It does not. We now make the following observations toward the implementation of such a programme:

(1). Only  states are present. The approximate  symmetry of non strange hadrons has for the multiplet ,  and  (15 rep) and for the baryons  and  the 20 dimensional symmetric multiplet (submultiplet of 56 of ). This tells us that  and  are cubic functions of the quark wave function.

In the skyrmion theory  () is missing. One must decouple isospin from spin. For that one should transform the skyrmion rotation

 
but also by deformation

 
so that one has


 
with

 
Then one has  degrees of freedom instead of  and  and  can be decoupled.

(2). In the skyrmion theory wave functions of  are linear in  and  is cubic in . The  symmetry between  and  is lost.

It can be recovered by having both  and  being cubic in   and . Then we can ask what do the  (linear in  and ) and the  (quadratic in  and ) represent? If one has the color degree of freedom, necessary for fermionic quantization, these states will be colored. Then it is natural to associate  linear functions with the quark (cubic root of the Skyrme soliton) and  with the diquark (th root of the skyrmion).

