We see that most everything is improved (some spectacularly). Except for the magnetic properties of the nucleon, the predictions derived from the model are in excellent agreement with the experimental values. Inclusion of the effect of vector mesons could change and improve the results significantly since the virtual photon can make a transition to the  and  mesons in the vector dominance scenarios. Possible improvement of the predicted values of the magnetic properties will be discussed below. 

In the generalized model (as is also in  case) we find that the calculated nucleon charge densities oscillate within the nucleons, a peculiar future of nucleon substructure. It is well known, from the deep inelastic scattering experiments, that nucleons have point-like constituents. Since the quark degrees of freedom are integrated out in the Skyrme model, we expect the substructure of the nucleons not to be point-like. Therefore the oscillatory behavior of the charge densities may be due to interference effect of the constituents, which is similar to the quark interference effect found in the bag model.  

Excellent agreement with the experimental value of  (=186 MeV) suggests that  model could serve as a better description of the nucleons. The reason might be that composite model associated with the Lagrangian  describes an effective hadronic theory based on QCD with the color group . The baryon consisting of  quarks are in a spatially symmetric ground state. In that case the current  could be interpreted as a quark number current, so that the baryon has quark number 3 for . Under spin and isospin transformations, the skyrmion matrix

 
has same transformation properties as the nucleon matrix of spin states  and  ()

 
with left and right multiplications being respectively associated with spin and isospin rotations. Now  and  which form the 20-dimensional symmetric representation of the spin-isospin group  are cubic functions of the elements of the underlying quark matrix

 
that can be taken to be proportional to . When the color group is  and  is quantized fermionically, it is possible to obtain the symmetric  representation for the  system that is cubic in . Four of these twenty cubic functions, which are eigenstates of the Hamiltonian, are associated with . They have both spin and isospin  and can be put in a  matrix form , where  with 

 
 being a singlet in spin and isospin. The remaining 16 cubic functions correspond to the wave functions of the  resonances. 

Since the quark has a baryon number  and the matrix  gives baryon number , it is natural to interpret the r dependence of the quark in the nucleon as being given by r. Then the quark matrix could be split into the form

 
in a static approximation. The  and  wave functions would then be associated with the cubic functions of the elements of  as well as being cubic in . The fermionic quantization is preferable for eliminating the higher excited states of the skyrmion represented by higher order polynomials in  that are eigenstates of the Hamiltonian. A convincing derivation of  composite Skyrme Lagrangian from QCD theory of quarks and gluons with color group  is still lacking. For the moment one can regard it as a phenomenological model that gives reasonable quantitative predictions. We shall deal with this issue and the wave functions of the  resonances written in terms of the cubic functions in a forthcoming publication. For now we give a brief introduction to this subject.

