where  and the covariant derivative  with
 
We see that the Lagrangian in Eq.() gives a Dirac equation for the nucleons (, which contains both the vector and the pseudoscalar meson-nucleon interactions through the covariant derivatives.

These examples show that gauge potentials can be obtained from the decompositions of larger algebra into a subalgebra and a coset. Gauge bosons, which take on special roles in the model originally, can be combined with the fundamental mesons to form a single multiplet so that all mesons are treated equally in the larger symmetry group. 

Fermionic Quantization 
Earlier we quantized the skyrmion by rotating the soliton solution by the  time-dependent matrix . The canonical conjugate matrix of  is given by

 
and the Hamiltonian is obtained from

 
Although at the classical level  and  are commuting variables, after quantization they become operators and are no longer commuting. We can either perform bosonic quantization
 
 

 
or fermionic quantization

 

 
that give the same algebra of the spin operators formed by the 's and 's. In the bosonic quantization, operators  commute among themselves, allowing particle states be described in terms of power functions in  of arbitrary orders. On the other hand, in the case of fermionic quantization, the  anticommute among themselves so that states with two or more identical  do not exist, and the powers in  of the state functions are limited. In the case when we take  to be fermionic, then the cubic functions for  vanishes.

To overcome this difficulty, we consider the same problem which occurred in the quark model when the problem arose of putting three spin up  quarks together to form   state. To conform with Pauli exclusion principle, three colors had to be introduced in the quark model to make the state antisymmetric in permuting any two quarks. In a similar sense, we now triple the number of variables in the Skyrme model by introducing two more matrices  and  in addition to the matrix , and require the new Lagrangian to be invariant under the permutations of ,  and . The color group  is replaced by the discrete subgroup . In general for  expansion, the color group  is replaced by , and there will be  different matrices. We propose a new Lagrangian that accommodates the new degrees of freedom

 

We note that the time dependent parts of  remain unchanged, so we only have to concentrate on the time derivatives of 

 

